Lessons that can be learned today from the Cuban Crisis
“Thirteen Days” (“Thirteen Days”), a new film about the Cuban Crisis, will soon be released in cinemas across numerous countries.
Everyone should watch this film, not only because it deals with the past, but also because it offers insights into current events – particularly regarding the controversies surrounding a US national missile defense system and the various regional discussions in India and Pakistan, Taiwan and China, North and South Korea, which could escalate into a nuclear conflict one day.
On October 16, 1962, President John F. Kennedy summoned his closest advisors to the White House.
Aerial photographs of the region had revealed the construction of a nuclear weapons deployment site in Cuba.
The decisions made in the following thirteen days and the decisions that could not be made could have led to the outbreak of a nuclear war.
The film illustrates what took place in the White House during these days.
Tape recordings made during President Kennedy's presidency played a significant role in the creation of the film.
Following the film's premiere in America, the Kennedy School of Government at Harvard launched a discussion round that should examine the film and the crisis it deals with.
Participants in this round included, among others: Robert McNamara, the Defense Minister under President Kennedy; Theodore Sorensen, one of Kennedy's close advisors and speechwriters; Ernest R. May, a professor of history at Harvard, who wrote a book on the "Kennedy Tapes"; and finally Graham Allison, a professor of political science at Harvard, who 30 years ago presented a classic study on the Cuban Crisis, the work "Essence of Decision".
Moreover, Peter A. Almond, the film's producer, was present.
Although the filmic portrayal of the topic was criticized in various points, the discussants were able to agree that the film accurately represents the problems and pressure that President Kennedy faced, just as they were in reality.
What conclusions can be drawn today from the Cuban Crisis?
Theodore Sorensen summarized them as follows:
• Advisors must play their role in the event of a crisis, but it is solely the President who ultimately bears the responsibility.
Most of Kennedy's advisors – both civilian and military – wanted to attack Cuba at the time.
It was only through Kennedy's sober analysis and probing questions that alternatives and dangers could be shown, which were crucial in determining the consequences.
· It is necessary to understand how an opponent thinks; communication channels must also remain open.
Driving an opponent into a corner without keeping diplomatic channels open, which enable understanding of the opposing side's situation, could prove disastrous.
· The United States relies on allies.
Kennedy acted this way because he had the support of NATO, other allies, and world opinion.
· A certain timeframe is necessary for making good decisions.
When lives or death are at stake, a politician cannot allow the media to pressure him into making a decision.
The fact that a week passed in which all involved factors were carefully examined and weighed was crucial for the outcome.
But would such a timeframe for deliberation even exist today in the face of modern mass media?
Robert McNamara emphasized the need to put oneself in the opponent's position.
In one of the most criticized scenes of the film, McNamara explains to a warlike admiral that the sea blockade imposed by Kennedy on Cuba was primarily intended to send a signal to Chairman Khrushchev about Kennedy's intentions, and not meant to stop specific Soviet ships.
Could Kennedy have acted even more calmly?
After all, the US had also stationed atomic warheads near the USSR.
Khrushchev's decision to station missiles in Cuba only reflected this policy.
However, Kennedy was concerned about the consequences that the deployment of Soviet missiles in Cuba would have had in relation to Berlin.
The pressure of nuclear weapons on Cuba would have further complicated the defense of Berlin, which was part of Khrushchev's strategy.
Ultimately, "the Berlin Crisis was resolved due to the results of the Cuban Crisis," as historian Ernest May claimed.
"It will soon be too late," was a widely spread argument that Kennedy heard from his advisors.
The advisors wanted to attack Cuba, even while the missiles – as they assumed – were on their way to Cuba by sea.
A US force of approximately 180,000 men was prepared for an invasion; there were even plans for a blitz bombing that would have been larger in scale than the NATO attack in Kosovo sixty years later. “I needed thirty years,” McNamara said, “to find out that there were already nuclear weapons on Cuba: 162 warheads, and of those, 90 strategic nuclear warheads.”
McNamara received this information during a meeting with Fidel Castro.
He asked Castro the following three questions: 1) Did you know about it?
2) If so, what did you recommend?
3) What would the consequences have been for Cuba?
Castro replied: "I knew about it.
And I explicitly recommended that nuclear weapons be used.
I knew that this would have led to the extermination of Cuba."
Castro and – to a greater extent – his comrade Che Guevara were willing to let Cuba burn, so that their country would become a martyr in the fight for world revolution!
An invasion would have had the potential consequences of the deaths of 80 million US Americans and the destruction of Cuba, simply because the Kennedy administration lacked sufficient knowledge of the facts (a common phenomenon when a politician has to make a decision alone).
McNamara is convinced that an invasion "undoubtedly" would have led to a Soviet nuclear attack against the US.
Khrushchev's control over the Soviet military on Cuba was limited: U2 planes flying over the Cuban airspace were shot at despite explicit contrary orders from the Chairman.
A difficult question that did not arise during this debate at Harvard is the following: What would have happened if the opponent had not been Khrushchev, who during the crisis distinguished himself by rational behavior, but rather an opponent like Saddam Hussein, Kim Jong Il, or a fundamentalist?
In the face of the spread of nuclear weapons, this danger could one day become a reality.
The current discussions about a limited missile defense and the threat of nuclear blackmail by rogue states should be conducted in light of this terrifying but entirely realistic thought.
Harvard has launched a new website on the internet, where the essential documents about the Cuban Crisis as well as the current nuclear threats can be found: www.cubanmissilecrisis.org.
